final-ratings/|archive-date=March 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n! style=\"font-size:small;\"| [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319]]\n! style=\"background:#fc9;\" | #85<ref name=\"2018-2019AvgRatings\"/>\n! style=\"background:#fc9;\" | #40<ref name=\"2018-2019AvgRatings\"/>\n! style=\"background:#fc9;\" | 5.15<ref name=\"2018-2019AvgRatings\"/>\n|-\n! style=\"background:#F9F9F9;text-align:center\"|[[How to Get Away with Murder (season 6)|6]]\n! <small>TBA</small>\n| style=\"font-size:small; text-align: center;\"| {{Start date|2019|9|26}}\n! 2.43<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/thursday-final-ratings-september-26-2019/|title='Young Sheldon' adjusts up, 'A Million Little Things' and 'Evil' adjust down: Thursday final ratings|last=Rejent|first=Joseph|work=TV by the Numbers|date=September 27, 2019|accessdate=September 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928220146/https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/thursday-final-ratings-september-26-2019/|archive-date=September 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: center;\"| <small>TBA</small>\n! <small>TBA</small>\n! style=\"font-size:small;\"| [[2019\u201320 United States network television schedule|2019\u201320]]\n! style=\"background:#fc9;\" | <small>TBA</small>\n! style=\"background:#fc9;\" | <small>TBA</small>\n! style=\"background:#fc9;\" | <small>TBA</small>\n|}\n\n===Accolades===\n {{multiple image\n| footer = Both [[Viola Davis|Davis]] (''left'') and [[Cicely Tyson|Tyson]] (''right'') received critical acclaim for their performances.\n| image1 = Viola Davis (cropped).jpg\n| width1 = 140\n| alt1 = \n| image2 = Cicely Tyson 2012 Shankbone 2.JPG\n| width2 = 151\n| alt2 = \n| align = left}}\nThe first season of the series was awarded [[American Film Institute Awards 2014|Television Program of the Year]] by the [[American Film Institute]] and won [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]] at the [[46th NAACP Image Awards]] and [[26th GLAAD Media Awards]]. The series was also nominated for Favorite New TV Drama at the [[41st People's Choice Awards]] and TV Drama of the Year at the [[GALECA]] awards. In 2016 the second season was nominated for Outstanding Drama Series at the 47th NAACP Image Awards, Favorite Network TV Drama at the [[42nd People's Choice Awards]] and Outstanding Drama Series at the [[27th GLAAD Media Awards]].\n \n[[Viola Davis]] became the first black woman to win a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]], also winning two [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]] for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Performance in a Drama Series]] and the NAACP Image Awards for [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Actress in a Drama Series]]. Davis also received nominations from the [[Golden Globe Awards]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actress in a Television Series]], the [[Critics' Choice Television Awards|Critics' Choice Awards]] for [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Actress in a Drama Series|Best Actress in a Drama Series]], and the [[Television Critics Association]] at the [[TCA Awards]] for [[TCA Award for Individual Achievement in Drama|Individual Achievement in Drama]]. Other cast members have also received recognition for their performances, with Alfred Enoch and Aja Naomi King being nominated by the [[NAACP]] as [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]] and [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series]] at the NAACP Image Awards. [[Cicely Tyson]] was nominated for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actress]] at the 2015 Primetime Emmy Awards. [[Glynn Turman]] was nominated for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actor]] at the 2019 Primetime Emmy Awards.\n{{clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Nominee(s)\n! Result\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Ref.\n|-\n| 2014\n| [[American Film Institute Awards 2014|American Film Institute Awards]]\n|[[American Film Institute Awards 2014#Television programs|Television Program of the Year]]\n|''How to Get Away with Murder''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.afi.com/and-the-honorees-are/ |title=American Film Institute Awards |date=December 8, 2014 |accessdate=December 8, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227024308/http://blog.afi.com/and-the-honorees-are/ |archive-date=December 27, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"19\" |2015\n| [[BET Awards 2015|BET Awards]]\n| [[BET Award for Best Actor & Actress|Best Actress]]\n| [[Viola Davis]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/music/news/bet-awards-nominations-2015-chris-brown-nicki-minaj-1201499466/ |title=Chris Brown, Nicki Minaj Lead 2015 BET Awards Nominations |work=Variety |accessdate=May 18, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150523221354/http://variety.com/2015/music/news/bet-awards-nominations-2015-chris-brown-nicki-minaj-1201499466/ |archive-date=May 23, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[5th Critics' Choice Television Awards|Critics' Choice Television Awards]]\n| [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Actress in a Drama Series|Best Actress in a Drama Series]]\n| Viola Davis\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/critics-choice-television-awards-nominations-2015-list-1201421320 |title=Critics' Choice Television Awards Nominations 