{"title_page": "Timeline of the feminist art movement in New Zealand", "text_new": "This is a timeline of the [[feminist art movement]] in [[New Zealand]] (or Aotearoa/New Zealand as it is often known in inclusive circles). It lists important figures, collectives, publications, exhibitions and moments that have contributed to discussion and development of the movement. For the indigenous [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] population, the emergence of the [[feminist art movement]] broadly coincided with the emergence of [[M\u0101ori Renaissance]].\n\n==1970s==\n\n'''1972'''\n\nThe feminist publication [[Broadsheet (magazine)|''Broadsheet'']] is co-founded by Anne Else and [[Sandra Coney]] in [[Auckland]]. It is New Zealand's first feminist magazine, and provides regular arts coverage. It ceases publication in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Else|first1=Anne|title=Gender inequalities - Areas of discrimination|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/photograph/28622/broadsheet|website=Te Ara - The Online Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=21 February 2016|date=15 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''1974'''\n\nFeminist poet [[Heather McPherson]] starts The Women Artists Group in Christchurch and begins working towards establishing the women's art journal ''Spiral,'' and the Spiral Collective.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/spiral-collectives/in-the-beginning-there-was-heather-d2ebbf4dd63c|title=In the beginning there was Heather.|last=Evans|first=Marian|date=31 May 2016|website=Spiral Collective|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''1975'''\n\nThe [[Robert McDougall Art Gallery]] in Christchurch (now the [[Christchurch Art Gallery]]) organises ''Women's Art: An Exhibition of Six Women Artists'' to mark International Women's Year. The exhibition is curated by artist [[Allie Eagle]], then Exhibitions Officer at the gallery.<ref>{{cite book|title=Women's Art: An Exhibition of Six Women Artists|date=1975|publisher=Robert McDougall Art Gallery|location=Christchurch|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/media/uploads/2010_08/WomansArt1975.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nWorks from photographer [[Fiona Clark (photographer)|Fiona Clark]]'s series 'Dance Party', taken at a gay lib dance party at Auckland University in 1974, are withdrawn from the touring photography exhibition ''[[The Active Eye]]'' after accusations of indecency.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wells|first1=Peter|title=Incandescent Moment: Fiona Clark's Go Girl|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Autumn 2003|issue=106|url=http://www.art-newzealand.com/Issue106/Clark.htm}}</ref>\n\n'''1976'''\n\nThe women's art journal ''Spiral'' begins publication.<ref name=\"Cook\">{{cite web|last1=Cook|first1=Megan|title=Women\u2019s movement - Arts and spirituality|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/womens-movement/page-9|website=Te Ara - The Online Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=21 February 2016|date=13 July 2012}}</ref> The ''International Women's Film Festival'' tours Dunedin, Christchurch, Wellington and Auckland.\n\n'''1977'''\n\nMembers of Women's artists groups, including [[Heather McPherson]] and  [[Allie Eagle]], work together to produce the Women's Art Environment at the Canterbury Society of Arts.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1977|title=The exhibitions : United Women's Convention 3\u20138 June|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/media/uploads/2010_08/1977-05-73.pdf|journal=CSA News|doi=|pmid=|access-date=17 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Else|first1=Anne|title=Gender inequalities - Arts and culture|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/photograph/28656/womens-art-environment-1977|website=Te Ara: The Online Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=McPherson|first=Heather|last2=Eagle|first2=Allie|last3=Keir|first3=Anna|last4=Paul|first4=Joanna|last5=Johnson|first5=Rosemary|year=1978|title=The Women's Environment at the '77 Women's Convention|url=|journal=Spiral (Christchurch, N.Z.)|issue= 3|pages=24\u201340|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''1978'''\n\n[[Allie Eagle]] show the works ''This woman died I care'' (based on a banned photograph of a woman who died after having an illegal abortion) and ''Empathy for a Rape Trial Victim''; the exhibition stokes controversy and the artist receives hate mail.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zusters|first1=Jane|title=Allie Eagle: Artist|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Summer 1994\u20131995|issue=73|pages=53\u201357}}</ref>\n\n'''1979'''\n\nThe Wellington Women's Gallery opens.<ref name ='Cook'/> Founded by Marian Evans, Anna Keir and Bridie Lonie the gallery was established as a non-profit, designed to 'support and promote women artists\u2019.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Evans|first1=Marian|title=They Might Have Completely Forgotten Us|url=https://medium.com/spiral-collectives/they-might-have-completely-forgotten-us-26b55cd68e69#.qdmzqosww|website=Spiral Collectives|accessdate=10 April 2016|date=9 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe National Art Gallery (now the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]]) establishes the Women's Art Archives, designed to collect the 'existing, neglected work by women and keep track of new work'. The archive is expanded to include Australian and Pacific women artists.<ref name ='Cook'/>\n\n==1980s==\n\n'''1980'''\n\nThe National Art Gallery stages the exhibition ''Women in Communication,'' curated by exhibitions officer Louise Upton. It includes an open forum to support prints and photographs from New Zealand women artists. Work by [[Robin White (artist)|Robin White]], [[Vivian Lynn]], Kate Coolahan and Gillian Chaplin were shown. The exhibition toured to [[Palmerston North]] and [[Whangarei]] and included video tapes from the Los Angeles Women's Video Centre.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Welsh|first=Robyn|date=1 September 1980|title=A gentle triumph for feminist art...but this faintly discriminatory National Gallery show may never be repeated|url=|journal=New Zealand Woman's Weekly}}</ref>\n\n'''1981'''\n\nThe [[Wellington Women's Gallery]] stages the exhibition ''Mothers'', which tours New Zealand throughout 1981-1982.<ref name=\"Cull\">{{cite journal|last1=Cull|first1=Chloe|title=Themes in M\u0101ori Women\u2019s Art: How the Body \u2018Speaks\u2019 Within the Work of M\u0101ori Women Artists of the Seventies and Eighties|journal=Oculus|date=2014|url=http://static1.squarespace.com/static/53bb2870e4b0dfc914b2b65a/t/5494bf88e4b050c0df015455/1419034504754/Oculus2014Web_Cull.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''1982'''\n\nThe [[F1 Sculpture Project]] is staged in a large disused factory building on Tory Street in Wellington. A significant number of female artists make temporary installation pieces and a range of events were staged, including a two-day Women Sculptors Seminar.<ref>{{cite web|title=Factory 1 (F1) Sculpture Project 1982|url=http://thecommunityarchive.org.nz/node/65922/description|website=The Community Archive|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Strathdee|first1=Barbara|title=Women Artists at the F1 New Zealand Sculpture Project|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Autumn 1983|issue=26}}</ref>\n\n[[Vivian Lynn]] shows her major sculptural work [http://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/object/840813 ''Guarden gates''], now in the collection of the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kirker|first1=Anne|title=Vivian Lynn's Garden Gates|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Autumn 1983|issue=26|url=http://www.art-newzealand.com/Issues21to30/lynn.htm|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vivian Lynn talks about her work Guarden gates, 1982|url=http://blog.tepapa.govt.nz/2010/10/29/vivian-lynn-talks-about-her-work-guarden-gates-1982/|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|accessdate=31 December 2014|date=29 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Feminist Art Network group is established in Auckland, advocating for an increased profile for work by women and feminist work.<ref>{{cite web|title=Feminist Art Network Archive|url=http://www.aucklandartgallery.com/explore-art-and-ideas/archives/19595|website=Auckland Art Gallery|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''1983'''\n\nThe national art magazine ''Art New Zealand'' dedicates its Autumn issue to female artists and the women's art movement. Art historian [[Cheryll Sotheran]] writes an overview of the current state and reception of women's art in New Zealand, noting  that 'most critics in New Zealand avoid or condemn exhibitions of women's art which use gender difference as a political weapon. The women whose art receives favourable reviews (or in many cases any reviews at all) are those whose work fits the modernist mould, are not feminists, are asexual and apolitical.'<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sotheran|first1=Cheryll|title=Replacing Women in Art History|url=http://www.art-newzealand.com/Issues21to30/replacing.htm|website=Art New Zealand|accessdate=21 February 2016|date=Autumn 1983}}</ref>\n\nHaeata, the M\u0101ori women\u2019s art collective, is established in Wellington. Members include [[Keri Kaa]], [[Patricia Grace]], [[Robyn Kahukiwa]] and [[Irihapeti Ramsden]]. It supports a number of significant female M\u0101ori artists and produces and tours exhibitions.<ref name ='Cull'/>\n\n[[Bronwynne Cornish]] is commissioned by the [[Auckland Art Gallery]] to produce a solo work and creates a multi-part ceramic installation titled ''Dedicated to the Kindness of Mothers''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Eastmond | first1=Elizabeth | title=Bronwynne Cornish's 'Dedicated to the kindness of mothers' | journal=Art New Zealand | date=Autumn 1984 | issue=30|url=http://www.art-newzealand.com/Issues21to30/cornish.htm}}</ref> \nIn April, [[Gretchen Albrecht]] selects work for a group exhibition arranged by the Outreach Gallery in Auckland,  ''New Works By Women''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rosier|first1=Pat|title=New Works By Women, 1983|journal=Broadsheet|date=June 1983|issue=110|pages=42}}</ref>\n\nIn June, Juliet Batten facilitates ''The Menstrual Maze'' at Greer's Factory in Auckland.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nicholson|first1=Bronwen|title=The Menstrual Maze|journal=Broadsheet|date=September 1983|issue=112|pages=46}}</ref>\nThe June issue of feminist magazine ''Broadsheet'' includes a special feature on feminist artists. It includes Batten's article 'What is a feminist artist?'.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Batten|first1=Juliet|title=What is a feminist artist?|journal=Broadsheet|date=June 1983|issue=110}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Broadsheet 110, June 1983: 'Special feature on feminist art'|url=http://best-of-3.blogspot.co.nz/2016/03/broadsheet-110-june-1983-special.html|website=Best of 3|accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n1983 also sees the founding of [[Aotearoa Moananui a Kiwa Weavers]], a government funding stream specific to female-dominated art forms, M\u0101ori and Pacific weaving. It is now known as [[Te Roopu Raranga Whatu o Aotearoa]] and M\u0101ori-only.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maoriart.org.nz/weavers-c-52_75.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304153600/http://www.maoriart.org.nz/weavers-c-52_75.html |archivedate=2012-03-04 }}</ref>\n\n'''1984'''\n\n[[Robyn Kahukiwa]] exhibits her series of paintings ''Wahine toa: women of M\u0101ori myth''; the paintings are also reproduced in a book with text by [[Patricia Grace]].<ref name='Mane-Wheoki'/>\n\n'''1985'''\n\nArtist Juliet Batten leads the 'One Hundred Women' event at [[Te Henga (Bethells Beach)]] as part of the ANZART project.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barton|first1=Christina|title=Post-object and conceptual art - What is post-object art|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/photograph/43823/one-hundred-women|website=Te Ara - The online encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''1986'''\n\nThe journal ''Antic'' is launched. Art historian [[Tina Barton]] describes it as 'one forum for a more analytical explication of feminist theory and its applications in the field of literature, criticism and the visual arts, which could be seen as an alternative to the ''Broadsheet'' or ''Art New Zealand'' models.' It ceases publication in 1990.<ref name ='Barton 1993'>{{cite journal|last1=Barton|first1=Christina|title=Ten Years On: Reviewing the terrain for women in art in New Zealand|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Spring 1993|issue=68|pages=50\u201352}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Antic 1986 - 1990: full list of contents|url=http://best-of-3.blogspot.co.nz/2016/03/antic-1986-1990-full-list-of-contents.html|website=Best of 3|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nArt critic Lita Barrie delivers a paper, 'Remissions: toward a deconstruction of phallic unequivocality: deferrals', at the Critic's Conference at the National Art Gallery. Informed by contemporary French theory and calling for a 'critical feminist art practice', Barrie attacked the essentialist form of feminist art practice common at the time, sending 'shock waves through the community of women artists to whom her paper was addressed'.<ref name = 'Barton 1993'/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rice|first1=Rebecca|last2=Williams|first2=Mark|title=Criticism and the arts - Issues of identity, 1960s onwards|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/criticism-and-the-arts/page-4|website=Te Ara - The Online Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first edition of Anne Kirker's ''New Zealand women artists'' is published by Reed Methuen.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kirker|first1=Anne|title=New Zealand women artists|date=1986|publisher=Reed Methuen|location=Auckland|isbn=0474001814}}</ref>\n\nElizabeth Eastmond and Merimeri Penfold's ''Women and the Arts in New Zealand: Forty Works 1936\u20131986'' is published by Penguin Books.<ref name ='Eastmond and Penfold>{{cite book|last1=Penfold|first1=Merimeri|last2=Eastmond|first2=Elizabeth|title=Women and the Arts in New Zealand: Forty Works 1936\u20131986|date=1986|publisher=Auckland|location=Penguin Books|isbn=014009234X}}</ref>\n\nThe Haeata collective organises the exhibition ''Karanga Karanga'', which shows in Auckland, Wellington and Gisborne.<ref name ='Cull'/>\n\n[[Vivian Lynn]] shows ''Gates of the Goddess \u2013 a southern crossing attended by the Goddess'' at the [[Govett-Brewster Art Gallery]]; the work is now in the collection of the [[Auckland Art Gallery]]).<ref name='Eastmond and Penfold'/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cook|first1=Megan|title='Women's movement \u2013 Arts and spirituality'|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/artwork/27927/goddess-gates|website=Te Ara \u2013 the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=22 February 2016|date=16 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Women and the arts in New Zealand \u2013 Forty Works: 1936\u201386|last = Eastmond|first = Elizabeth|publisher = Penguin Books|year = 1986|isbn = 014009234X|location = Auckland|pages = |last2 = Penfold|first2 = Merimeri}}</ref>\n\n'''1988'''\n\nThe National Art Gallery organises an exhibition of the work of American artist [[Barbara Kruger]], curated by [[Jenny Harper]]. The exhibition is held at the Gallery's satellite contemporary art space, Shed 11. Kruger visits New Zealand for the opening of the exhibition and delivers a public lecture.<ref name=\"Clifford\">{{cite web|last1=Clifford|first1=Jess|title=Looking out, looking in|url=http://arts.tepapa.govt.nz/off-the-wall/7693/looking-in-looking-out|website=Off The Wall|publisher=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Untitled (We are unsuitable for framing)|url=http://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/object/36996|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nMarian Evans, Bridie Lonie and Tilly Lloyd co-edit ''A Women's picture book : 25 women artists of Aotearoa New Zealand''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Evans|first1=Marian|last2=Lonie|first2=Bridie|last3=Lloyd|first3=Tilly|title=A Women's picture book : 25 women artists of Aotearoa New Zealand|date=1988|publisher=GP Books|location=Wellington|isbn=0477013953}}</ref> The authors intend to include a number of M\u0101ori artists, including [[Irihapeti Ramsden]], [[Jacqueline Fraser]] and [[Robyn Kahukiwa]] but several withdraw after concerns about material included in the book which they felt to breach [[Tapu (Polynesian culture)|tapu]].<ref name=\"Mane-Wheoki\">{{cite web|last1=Mane-Wheoki|first1=Jonathan|title=Contemporary M\u0101ori art \u2013 ng\u0101 toi h\u014du - New developments in contemporary art|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/contemporary-maori-art-nga-toi-hou/page-3|website=Te Ara - The Online Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=21 February 2016|date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Shona Rapira Davies]] and [[Robyn Kahukiwa]] collaborate on the exhibition ''Whakamaemae'' ('To feel pain') at [[City Gallery Wellington]]; the exhibition includes Rapira Davies' major sculptural work ''Nga Morehu''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nga Morehu|url=http://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/object/43005|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''1989'''\n\nFollowing on from the exhibition of Kruger's work, National Art Gallery director [[Luit Bieringa]] curates an exhibition of work by photographer [[Cindy Sherman]], also staged at Shed 11.<ref name=\"Clifford\"/>\n\n==1990s==\n\n'''1990'''\n\nThis year marks New Zealand's sesquicentennial. A number of M\u0101ori women artists withdraw from the National Art Gallery's exhibition ''Kohia ko Taikaka Anake'' after learning that senior female artists will be made subordinate to senior male artists in its presentation.<ref name=\"Mane-Wheoki\"/> The  Haeata collective presents ''Hineteiwaiwa'', the \u2018womanhouse\u2019, for the ''Mana Tiriti'' exhibition at [[City Gallery Wellington]].<ref name=\"Mane-Wheoki\"/>\n\n'''1992'''\n\n[[Cheryll Sotheran]] is appointed as the founding CEO of the new [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]], which merges New Zealand's national museum and national art gallery.\n\n'''1993'''\n\nThis year marks the 100th anniversary of [[women's suffrage in New Zealand]].\n\n''Art New Zealand'' dedicates its Spring issue that year to female artists and feminist topics. Art historian Tina Barton is commissioned to write a review of the decade since the last issue of the magazine devoted to women artists.<ref name ='Barton 1993'/> A number of exhibitions exploring women in New Zealand's art history and feminist art issues are staged around the country, including ''[[Alter / Image]]'' in Wellington and Auckland, ''Mediatrix : new works by seven women artists'' at [[Artspace NZ|Artspace]] in Auckland (curated by Priscilla Pitts and featuring [[Mary-Louise Browne]], [[Denise Kum]], [[Julia Morison]], Marie Shannon, Deborah Smith, Aromea Tahiwi and [[Barbara Tuck]]); ''Unruly Practices'' (a series of solo projects by feminist artists living in Auckland - [[Carole Shepheard]], [[Claudia Pond Eyley]], Mary McIntyre, [[Christine Hellyar]] and [[Sylvia Siddell]]) at [[Auckland Art Gallery]], ''White Camellias : a century of women's artmaking in Canterbury'' and ''Women on women : art in Dunedin since 1893'' at the [[Dunedin Public Art Gallery]], curated by Linda Tyler.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mediatrix : new work by seven women artists : an exhibition to mark the centenary of women's suffrage in New Zealand|url=http://natlib.govt.nz/records/22161487|website=National Library of New Zealand|accessdate=25 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=White Camellias: A Century of Art Making by Canterbury Women|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/exhibitions/white-camellias|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=25 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Women on women : art in Dunedin since 1893|url=http://natlib.govt.nz/records/22206191|website=National Library of New Zealand|accessdate=25 December 2015}}</ref> ''Alter / Image'' was also one of four inaugural exhibitions, all featuring female artists, that marked the opening of [[City Gallery Wellington]] in its new location in the old Public Library building in Wellington's Civic Square; the others were ''[[Rosemarie Trockel]]'', ''Te Whare Puanga'' (recent weaving and tivaevae by Maori and Pacific Island women in Wellington) and ''He Tohu: The New Zealand Room'', a site-specific project by [[Jacqueline Fraser]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Exhibition advertisement|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Spring 1993|issue=68|page=unpaginated}}</ref> An updated version of Anne Kirker's 1986 book ''New Zealand Women Artists'' is published as ''New Zealand women artists : a survey of 150 years'' by Reed Methuen.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kirker|first1=Anne|title=New Zealand women artists : a survey of 150 years|date=1993|publisher=Auckland|location=Reed Methuen|isbn=9768097302}}</ref>\n\n'''1994'''\n\nAustralian art magazine ''Artlink'' devotes its Autumn issue to 'Art & the Feminist Project'. The issue features articles by New Zealand writers  [[Tina Barton]] ('Making (a) difference: Suffrage year celebrations and the visual arts in New Zealand') and Anne Kirker ('Re-orienting feminism in Aotearoa').<ref>{{cite web|title=Art & the Feminist Project|url=https://www.artlink.com.au/issues/1410/art-26-the-feminist-project/|website=Artlink|accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==2000s==\n\n'''2000'''\n\nThe [[Govett-Brewster Art Gallery]] stages ''In glorious dreams'', an exhibition of new work by women artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=In glorious dreams|url=http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/vwebv/holdingsInfo?bibId=610512|website=National Library of New Zealand catalogue|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2001'''\n\nArtist [[Jacqueline Fraser]] is selected, along with Peter Robinson, to represent New Zealand in its first participation at the [[Venice Biennale]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mane-Wheoki|first1=Jonathan|title=Contemporary M\u0101ori art \u2013 ng\u0101 toi h\u014du - Contemporary M\u0101ori art in the 2000s|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/contemporary-maori-art-nga-toi-hou/page-5|website=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''2002'''\n\nThe Govett-Brewster Art Gallery stages ''Go Girl'', a survey of the work of photographer Fiona Clark. The exhibition includes works withdrawn from the 1975 exhibition ''The Active Eye'' after accusations of indecency relating to their depiction of the LGBT community.<ref>{{cite web|title=Go Girl at New Plymouth\u2019s Govett-Brewster Gallery|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU0209/S00079/go-girl-at-new-plymouths-govett-brewster-gallery.htm|website=Scoop.co.nz|accessdate=23 February 2016|date=25 September 2002}}</ref>\n\n'''2004'''\n\nThe Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa stages ''Judy Darragh: So ... You Made It'', the only solo exhibition of a contemporary New Zealand artist presented at the museum between its opening in 1998 and the 'Toi Art' refreshment that opened in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Judy Darragh: So ... you made it?|url=http://www.tepapa.govt.nz/WhatsOn/exhibitions/Pages/JudyDarragh.aspx|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tonagrewa|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2008'''\n\nThe Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa presents the exhibition ''We are unsuitable for framing''. Curated by Charlotte Huddleston, the exhibition is titled after a work by Barbara Kruger held in the museum's collection and included in the artist's 1988 exhibition in Wellington. It includes works produced between 1974 and 2005 and aimed to explore 'aspects of identity, gender, sexuality, and mythology'.<ref>{{cite web|title=We are unsuitable for framing|url=http://www.tepapa.govt.nz/WhatsOn/exhibitions/Pages/WeAreUnsuitableForFraming.aspx|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2009'''\n\nThe [[Adam Art Gallery]] holds a workshop titled 'Out Loud: Using the \u2018F\u2019 Word Today', featuring a range of female curators and artists, to accompany its survey exhibition of the work of [[Vivian Lynn]], '' I, HERE, NOW Vivian Lynn''.<ref>{{cite web|title=February-March 2009|url=http://www.adamartgallery.org.nz/calendar/february-march/|website=Adam Art Gallery|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==2010 - present==\n\n'''2012'''\n\n[[The Dowse Art Museum]] stages the touring  exhibition ''In Spite of Ourselves: Approaching Documentary'', which includes a work by Qatari/US artist, Sophia Al-Maria, ''For Your Eyes Only'' (2007) which shows female members of a family preparing for a wedding in a space in a house only used by women and children. The artists requests that the video work only be shown to female visitors: when the museum complies with this request protests are made that men are being excluded from the museum.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Spite of Ourselves: Approaching Documentary|url=http://dowse.org.nz/exhibitions/detail/in-spite-of-ourselves-approaching-documentary|website=The Dowse Art Museum|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=In Spite of Everything|url=http://dowse.org.nz/news/blog/2012/in-spite-of-everything|website=The Dowse Art Museum|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2013'''\n\nWriter Thomasin Sleigh publishes an analysis of the contemporary editorial approach of ''Art New Zealand'', concluding that 'the artist most likely for Art New Zealand to run an article on would be a Pakeha painter, and his work would most likely be written about by a Pakeha man employed by an academic institution.'<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sleigh|first1=Thomasin|title=The Stuttering Conversation:  Art New Zealand in 2013|url=http://lumiere.net.nz/index.php/art-new-zealand-in-2013/|website=The Lumiere Reader|accessdate=22 February 2016|date=21 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''2014'''\n\nArt History honours students at the University of Auckland organise ''Voicing the Visible'', an exhibition of female and feminist artists work from the university's collection for the Gus Fisher Gallery.<ref>{{cite web|title=Voicing the Visible|url=http://www.ingenio-magazine.com/voicing-the-visible/|website=Ingenio|publisher=University of Auckland Alumni organisation|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2015'''\n\n[[Enjoy Public Art Gallery]] in Wellington presents ''Enjoy Feminisms'', an exhibition programme that sought to demonstrate the multiple meanings of feminism to contemporary artists, and publishes ''Love Feminisms'', an online journal to accompany the exhibition programme.<ref>{{cite web|title=Enjoy Feminisms|url=http://www.enjoy.org.nz/node/3665|website=Enjoy Public Art Gallery|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Love Feminisms|url=http://journal.enjoy.org.nz/love-feminisms/editorial|website=Enjoy Public Art Gallery|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Adam Art Gallery]] presents ''Fragments of a World: Artists Working in Film and Photography 1973\u20131987'', curated by Dr Sandy Callister, an exhibition investigating 'the intersection of feminism, new technologies, and a disruptive epoch'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fragments of a World|url=http://www.adamartgallery.org.nz/past-exhibitions/10053/|website=Adam Art Gallery|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[The Dowse Art Museum]] in Lower Hutt organises an 'Art + Feminism' Wikipedia edit-a-thon to improve coverage of New Zealand women artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Art + Feminism edit-a-thon|url=http://dowse.org.nz/events/art-feminism-wikipedia-edit-a-thon|website=The Dowse Art Museum|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2016'''\n\nThe Dowse Art Museum organises 'Four Waves of Feminism', a symposium exploring current and historical feminist art, activity and research.<ref>{{cite web|title=Four Waves of Feminism|url=http://dowse.org.nz/events/four-waves-of-feminism|website=The Dowse Art Museum|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nBarbara Brookes' ''A History of New Zealand Women'' is published by [[Bridget Williams Books]]. Heavily illustrated with the work of women artists including [[Olivia Spencer Bower]], [[Rita Angus]], [[Margaret Stoddart]] and [[Louise Henderson]], the reproductions are presented 'not simply as illustrations for the immediate text but as a narrative in themselves. ... this is, presenting a woman's perspective.'<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brookes|first1=Barbara|title=A history of New Zealand women|date=2016|publisher=Bridget Williams Books|location=Wellington|isbn=9780908321476|page=486}}</ref>\n\nThe Adam Art Gallery presents ''Bad Visual Systems'', an exhibition by Berlin-based, New Zealand-born artist Ruth Buchanan. For the exhibition Buchanan shows the work of German artists Judith Hopf and [[Marianne Wex]]. The exhibition presents panels from Wex's photographic book ''Let\u2019s Take Back Our Space''; sheets from the book had been printed in a 1984 edition of the feminist magazine ''Broadsheet'' when Wex was living in Wellington.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bad Visual Systems|url=http://www.adamartgallery.org.nz/current-exhibition/|website=Adam Art Gallery|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2018'''\n\n2018 marks the 125th anniversary of women's suffrage in New Zealand.\n\nChristchurch Art Gallery presents ''We Do This'', an exhibition of work by women artists. largely from the gallery's permanent collection, in a 'recharged contemporary hang to mark 125 years of women\u2019s suffrage.'<ref>{{cite web |title=We Do This |url=https://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/exhibitions/we-do-this |website=Christchurch Art Gallery Te Puna o Waiwhet\u016b |accessdate=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Dowse Art Museum presents \"Embodied Knowledge\", an exhibition of \"significant sculptural works made by women artists during a tumultuous period of Aotearoa New Zealand\u2019s art history\" featuring older and new works by Christine Hellyar, Maureen Lander, Vivian Lynn, Pauline Rhodes, The Estate of L. Budd.<ref>{{cite web |title=Embodied Knowledge |url=http://dowse.org.nz/exhibitions/detail/embodied-knowledge |website=dowse.org.nz |accessdate=25 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> A pendant exhibition, ''Can Tame Anything'', features work by a newer generation of women artists and collectives; Ruth Buchanan, Alicia Frankovich, Mata Aho Collective, Sriwhana Spong.<ref>{{cite web |title=Can Tame Anything |url=http://dowse.org.nz/exhibitions/detail/can-tame-anything |website=dowse.org.nz |accessdate=25 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''2019'''\n\nThe Auckland Art Gallery presents ''Guerrilla Girls: Reinventing the \u2018F\u2019 Word \u2013 Feminism!'', an exhibition of work by the famous feminist art collective [[Guerilla Girls]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Guerrilla Girls: Reinventing the \u2018F\u2019 Word \u2013 Feminism! |url=https://www.aucklandartgallery.com/whats-on/exhibition/guerrilla-girls-reinventing-the-f-word-feminism |website=Auckland Art Gallery |accessdate=25 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The exhibition includes statistical analysis presented in the collective's signature format of the proportion of exhibitions of women artists at the gallery.\n\n[[The Spinoff]] publishes Anna Knox's investigative article 'Gender bias and art in Aotearoa: a Spinoff survey reveals the harsh reality'.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Knox |first1=Anna |title=Gender bias and art in Aotearoa: a Spinoff survey reveals the harsh reality |url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/art/30-09-2019/gender-bias-and-art-in-aotearoa-a-spinoff-survey-reveals-the-harsh-reality/ |website=The Spinoff |accessdate=25 October 2019 |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Feminism in New Zealand]]\n*[[List of New Zealand artists]]\n*[[Australian feminist art timeline]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Feminism}}\n{{Westernart}}\n\n<!-- STOP! Be warned that by using this process instead of Articles for Creation, this article is subject to scrutiny. As an article in \"mainspace\", it will be DELETED if there are problems, not just declined. If you wish to use AfC, please return to the Wizard and continue from there. -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feminist Art Movement}}\n[[Category:Art movements]]\n[[Category:Contemporary art]]\n[[Category:Feminist theory]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Political art]]\n[[Category:New Zealand art]]\n[[Category:Feminism in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "This is a timeline of the [[feminist art movement]] in [[New Zealand]] (or Aotearoa/New Zealand as it is often known in inclusive circles). It lists important figures, collectives, publications, exhibitions and moments that have contributed to discussion and development of the movement. For the indigenous [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] population, the emergence of the [[feminist art movement]] broadly coincided with the emergence of [[M\u0101ori Renaissance]].\n\n==1970s==\n\n'''1972'''\n\nThe feminist publication [[Broadsheet (magazine)|''Broadsheet'']] is co-founded by Anne Else and [[Sandra Coney]] in [[Auckland]]. It is New Zealand's first feminist magazine, and provides regular arts coverage. It ceases publication in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Else|first1=Anne|title=Gender inequalities - Areas of discrimination|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/photograph/28622/broadsheet|website=Te Ara - The Online Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=21 February 2016|date=15 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''1974'''\n\nFeminist poet [[Heather McPherson]] starts The Women Artists Group in Christchurch and begins working towards establishing the women's art journal ''Spiral,'' and the Spiral Collective.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/spiral-collectives/in-the-beginning-there-was-heather-d2ebbf4dd63c|title=In the beginning there was Heather.|last=Evans|first=Marian|date=31 May 2016|website=Spiral Collective|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''1975'''\n\nThe [[Robert McDougall Art Gallery]] in Christchurch (now the [[Christchurch Art Gallery]]) organises ''Women's Art: An Exhibition of Six Women Artists'' to mark International Women's Year. The exhibition is curated by artist [[Allie Eagle]], then Exhibitions Officer at the gallery.<ref>{{cite book|title=Women's Art: An Exhibition of Six Women Artists|date=1975|publisher=Robert McDougall Art Gallery|location=Christchurch|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/media/uploads/2010_08/WomansArt1975.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nWorks from photographer [[Fiona Clark (photographer)|Fiona Clark]]'s series 'Dance Party', taken at a gay lib dance party at Auckland University in 1974, are withdrawn from the touring photography exhibition ''[[The Active Eye]]'' after accusations of indecency.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wells|first1=Peter|title=Incandescent Moment: Fiona Clark's Go Girl|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Autumn 2003|issue=106|url=http://www.art-newzealand.com/Issue106/Clark.htm}}</ref>\n\n'''1976'''\n\nThe women's art journal ''Spiral'' begins publication.<ref name=\"Cook\">{{cite web|last1=Cook|first1=Megan|title=Women\u2019s movement - Arts and spirituality|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/womens-movement/page-9|website=Te Ara - The Online Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=21 February 2016|date=13 July 2012}}</ref> The ''International Women's Film Festival'' tours Dunedin, Christchurch, Wellington and Auckland.\n\n'''1977'''\n\nMembers of Women's artists groups, including [[Heather McPherson]] and  [[Allie Eagle]], work together to produce the Women's Art Environment at the Canterbury Society of Arts.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1977|title=The exhibitions : United Women's Convention 3\u20138 June|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/media/uploads/2010_08/1977-05-73.pdf|journal=CSA News|doi=|pmid=|access-date=17 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Else|first1=Anne|title=Gender inequalities - Arts and culture|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/photograph/28656/womens-art-environment-1977|website=Te Ara: The Online Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=McPherson|first=Heather|last2=Eagle|first2=Allie|last3=Keir|first3=Anna|last4=Paul|first4=Joanna|last5=Johnson|first5=Rosemary|year=1978|title=The Women's Environment at the '77 Women's Convention|url=|journal=Spiral (Christchurch, N.Z.)|issue= 3|pages=24\u201340|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''1978'''\n\n[[Allie Eagle]] show the works ''This woman died I care'' (based on a banned photograph of a woman who died after having an illegal abortion) and ''Empathy for a Rape Trial Victim''; the exhibition stokes controversy and the artist receives hate mail.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zusters|first1=Jane|title=Allie Eagle: Artist|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Summer 1994\u20131995|issue=73|pages=53\u201357}}</ref>\n\n'''1979'''\n\nThe Wellington Women's Gallery opens.<ref name ='Cook'/> Founded by Marian Evans, Anna Keir and Bridie Lonie the gallery was established as a non-profit, designed to 'support and promote women artists\u2019.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Evans|first1=Marian|title=They Might Have Completely Forgotten Us|url=https://medium.com/spiral-collectives/they-might-have-completely-forgotten-us-26b55cd68e69#.qdmzqosww|website=Spiral Collectives|accessdate=10 April 2016|date=9 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe National Art Gallery (now the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]]) establishes the Women's Art Archives, designed to collect the 'existing, neglected work by women and keep track of new work'. The archive is expanded to include Australian and Pacific women artists.<ref name ='Cook'/>\n\n==1980s==\n\n'''1980'''\n\nThe National Art Gallery stages the exhibition ''Women in Communication,'' curated by exhibitions officer Louise Upton. It includes an open forum to support prints and photographs from New Zealand women artists. Work by [[Robin White (artist)|Robin White]], [[Vivian Lynn]], Kate Coolahan and Gillian Chaplin were shown. The exhibition toured to [[Palmerston North]] and [[Whangarei]] and included video tapes from the Los Angeles Women's Video Centre.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Welsh|first=Robyn|date=1 September 1980|title=A gentle triumph for feminist art...but this faintly discriminatory National Gallery show may never be repeated|url=|journal=New Zealand Woman's Weekly}}</ref>\n\n'''1981'''\n\nThe [[Wellington Women's Gallery]] stages the exhibition ''Mothers'', which tours New Zealand throughout 1981-1982.<ref name=\"Cull\">{{cite journal|last1=Cull|first1=Chloe|title=Themes in M\u0101ori Women\u2019s Art: How the Body \u2018Speaks\u2019 Within the Work of M\u0101ori Women Artists of the Seventies and Eighties|journal=Oculus|date=2014|url=http://static1.squarespace.com/static/53bb2870e4b0dfc914b2b65a/t/5494bf88e4b050c0df015455/1419034504754/Oculus2014Web_Cull.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''1982'''\n\nThe [[F1 Sculpture Project]] is staged in a large disused factory building on Tory Street in Wellington. A significant number of female artists make temporary installation pieces and a range of events were staged, including a two-day Women Sculptors Seminar.<ref>{{cite web|title=Factory 1 (F1) Sculpture Project 1982|url=http://thecommunityarchive.org.nz/node/65922/description|website=The Community Archive|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Strathdee|first1=Barbara|title=Women Artists at the F1 New Zealand Sculpture Project|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Autumn 1983|issue=26}}</ref>\n\n[[Vivian Lynn]] shows her major sculptural work [http://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/object/840813 ''Guarden gates''], now in the collection of the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kirker|first1=Anne|title=Vivian Lynn's Garden Gates|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Autumn 1983|issue=26|url=http://www.art-newzealand.com/Issues21to30/lynn.htm|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vivian Lynn talks about her work Guarden gates, 1982|url=http://blog.tepapa.govt.nz/2010/10/29/vivian-lynn-talks-about-her-work-guarden-gates-1982/|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|accessdate=31 December 2014|date=29 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Feminist Art Network group is established in Auckland, advocating for an increased profile for work by women and feminist work.<ref>{{cite web|title=Feminist Art Network Archive|url=http://www.aucklandartgallery.com/explore-art-and-ideas/archives/19595|website=Auckland Art Gallery|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''1983'''\n\nThe national art magazine ''Art New Zealand'' dedicates its Autumn issue to female artists and the women's art movement. Art historian [[Cheryll Sotheran]] writes an overview of the current state and reception of women's art in New Zealand, noting  that 'most critics in New Zealand avoid or condemn exhibitions of women's art which use gender difference as a political weapon. The women whose art receives favourable reviews (or in many cases any reviews at all) are those whose work fits the modernist mould, are not feminists, are asexual and apolitical.'<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sotheran|first1=Cheryll|title=Replacing Women in Art History|url=http://www.art-newzealand.com/Issues21to30/replacing.htm|website=Art New Zealand|accessdate=21 February 2016|date=Autumn 1983}}</ref>\n\nHaeata, the M\u0101ori women\u2019s art collective, is established in Wellington. Members include [[Keri Kaa]], [[Patricia Grace]], [[Robyn Kahukiwa]] and [[Irihapeti Ramsden]]. It supports a number of significant female M\u0101ori artists and produces and tours exhibitions.<ref name ='Cull'/>\n\n[[Bronwynne Cornish]] is commissioned by the [[Auckland Art Gallery]] to produce a solo work and creates a multi-part ceramic installation titled ''Dedicated to the Kindness of Mothers''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Eastmond | first1=Elizabeth | title=Bronwynne Cornish's 'Dedicated to the kindness of mothers' | journal=Art New Zealand | date=Autumn 1984 | issue=30|url=http://www.art-newzealand.com/Issues21to30/cornish.htm}}</ref> \nIn April, [[Gretchen Albrecht]] selects work for a group exhibition arranged by the Outreach Gallery in Auckland,  ''New Works By Women''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rosier|first1=Pat|title=New Works By Women, 1983|journal=Broadsheet|date=June 1983|issue=110|pages=42}}</ref>\n\nIn June, Juliet Batten facilitates ''The Menstrual Maze'' at Greer's Factory in Auckland.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nicholson|first1=Bronwen|title=The Menstrual Maze|journal=Broadsheet|date=September 1983|issue=112|pages=46}}</ref>\nThe June issue of feminist magazine ''Broadsheet'' includes a special feature on feminist artists. It includes Batten's article 'What is a feminist artist?'.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Batten|first1=Juliet|title=What is a feminist artist?|journal=Broadsheet|date=June 1983|issue=110}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Broadsheet 110, June 1983: 'Special feature on feminist art'|url=http://best-of-3.blogspot.co.nz/2016/03/broadsheet-110-june-1983-special.html|website=Best of 3|accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n1983 also sees the founding of [[Aotearoa Moananui a Kiwa Weavers]], a government funding stream specific to female-dominated art forms, M\u0101ori and Pacific weaving. It is now known as [[Te Roopu Raranga Whatu o Aotearoa]] and M\u0101ori-only.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maoriart.org.nz/weavers-c-52_75.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304153600/http://www.maoriart.org.nz/weavers-c-52_75.html |archivedate=2012-03-04 }}</ref>\n\n'''1984'''\n\n[[Robyn Kahukiwa]] exhibits her series of paintings ''Wahine toa: women of M\u0101ori myth''; the paintings are also reproduced in a book with text by [[Patricia Grace]].<ref name='Mane-Wheoki'/>\n\n'''1985'''\n\nArtist Juliet Batten leads the 'One Hundred Women' event at [[Te Henga (Bethells Beach)]] as part of the ANZART project.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barton|first1=Christina|title=Post-object and conceptual art - What is post-object art|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/photograph/43823/one-hundred-women|website=Te Ara - The online encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''1986'''\n\nThe journal ''Antic'' is launched. Art historian [[Tina Barton]] describes it as 'one forum for a more analytical explication of feminist theory and its applications in the field of literature, criticism and the visual arts, which could be seen as an alternative to the ''Broadsheet'' or ''Art New Zealand'' models.' It ceases publication in 1990.<ref name ='Barton 1993'>{{cite journal|last1=Barton|first1=Christina|title=Ten Years On: Reviewing the terrain for women in art in New Zealand|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Spring 1993|issue=68|pages=50\u201352}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Antic 1986 - 1990: full list of contents|url=http://best-of-3.blogspot.co.nz/2016/03/antic-1986-1990-full-list-of-contents.html|website=Best of 3|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nArt critic Lita Barrie delivers a paper, 'Remissions: toward a deconstruction of phallic unequivocality: deferrals', at the Critic's Conference at the National Art Gallery. Informed by contemporary French theory and calling for a 'critical feminist art practice', Barrie attacked the essentialist form of feminist art practice common at the time, sending 'shock waves through the community of women artists to whom her paper was addressed'.<ref name = 'Barton 1993'/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rice|first1=Rebecca|last2=Williams|first2=Mark|title=Criticism and the arts - Issues of identity, 1960s onwards|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/criticism-and-the-arts/page-4|website=Te Ara - The Online Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first edition of Anne Kirker's ''New Zealand women artists'' is published by Reed Methuen.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kirker|first1=Anne|title=New Zealand women artists|date=1986|publisher=Reed Methuen|location=Auckland|isbn=0474001814}}</ref>\n\nElizabeth Eastmond and Merimeri Penfold's ''Women and the Arts in New Zealand: Forty Works 1936\u20131986'' is published by Penguin Books.<ref name ='Eastmond and Penfold>{{cite book|last1=Penfold|first1=Merimeri|last2=Eastmond|first2=Elizabeth|title=Women and the Arts in New Zealand: Forty Works 1936\u20131986|date=1986|publisher=Auckland|location=Penguin Books|isbn=014009234X}}</ref>\n\nThe Haeata collective organises the exhibition ''Karanga Karanga'', which shows in Auckland, Wellington and Gisborne.<ref name ='Cull'/>\n\n[[Vivian Lynn]] shows ''Gates of the Goddess \u2013 a southern crossing attended by the Goddess'' at the [[Govett-Brewster Art Gallery]]; the work is now in the collection of the [[Auckland Art Gallery]]).<ref name='Eastmond and Penfold'/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cook|first1=Megan|title='Women's movement \u2013 Arts and spirituality'|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/artwork/27927/goddess-gates|website=Te Ara \u2013 the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=22 February 2016|date=16 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Women and the arts in New Zealand \u2013 Forty Works: 1936\u201386|last = Eastmond|first = Elizabeth|publisher = Penguin Books|year = 1986|isbn = 014009234X|location = Auckland|pages = |last2 = Penfold|first2 = Merimeri}}</ref>\n\n'''1988'''\n\nThe National Art Gallery organises an exhibition of the work of American artist [[Barbara Kruger]], curated by [[Jenny Harper]]. The exhibition is held at the Gallery's satellite contemporary art space, Shed 11. Kruger visits New Zealand for the opening of the exhibition and delivers a public lecture.<ref name=\"Clifford\">{{cite web|last1=Clifford|first1=Jess|title=Looking out, looking in|url=http://arts.tepapa.govt.nz/off-the-wall/7693/looking-in-looking-out|website=Off The Wall|publisher=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Untitled (We are unsuitable for framing)|url=http://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/object/36996|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nMarian Evans, Bridie Lonie and Tilly Lloyd co-edit ''A Women's picture book : 25 women artists of Aotearoa New Zealand''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Evans|first1=Marian|last2=Lonie|first2=Bridie|last3=Lloyd|first3=Tilly|title=A Women's picture book : 25 women artists of Aotearoa New Zealand|date=1988|publisher=GP Books|location=Wellington|isbn=0477013953}}</ref> The authors intend to include a number of M\u0101ori artists, including [[Irihapeti Ramsden]], [[Jacqueline Fraser]] and [[Robyn Kahukiwa]] but several withdraw after concerns about material included in the book which they felt to breach [[Tapu (Polynesian culture)|tapu]].<ref name=\"Mane-Wheoki\">{{cite web|last1=Mane-Wheoki|first1=Jonathan|title=Contemporary M\u0101ori art \u2013 ng\u0101 toi h\u014du - New developments in contemporary art|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/contemporary-maori-art-nga-toi-hou/page-3|website=Te Ara - The Online Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=21 February 2016|date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Shona Rapira Davies]] and [[Robyn Kahukiwa]] collaborate on the exhibition ''Whakamaemae'' ('To feel pain') at [[City Gallery Wellington]]; the exhibition includes Rapira Davies' major sculptural work ''Nga Morehu''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nga Morehu|url=http://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/object/43005|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''1989'''\n\nFollowing on from the exhibition of Kruger's work, National Art Gallery director [[Luit Bieringa]] curates an exhibition of work by photographer [[Cindy Sherman]], also staged at Shed 11.<ref name=\"Clifford\"/>\n\n==1990s==\n\n'''1990'''\n\nThis year marks New Zealand's sesquicentennial. A number of M\u0101ori women artists withdraw from the National Art Gallery's exhibition ''Kohia ko Taikaka Anake'' after learning that senior female artists will be made subordinate to senior male artists in its presentation.<ref name=\"Mane-Wheoki\"/> The  Haeata collective presents ''Hineteiwaiwa'', the \u2018womanhouse\u2019, for the ''Mana Tiriti'' exhibition at [[City Gallery Wellington]].<ref name=\"Mane-Wheoki\"/>\n\n'''1992'''\n\n[[Cheryll Sotheran]] is appointed as the founding CEO of the new [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]], which merges New Zealand's national museum and national art gallery.\n\n'''1993'''\n\nThis year marks the 100th anniversary of [[women's suffrage in New Zealand]].\n\n''Art New Zealand'' dedicates its Spring issue that year to female artists and feminist topics. Art historian Tina Barton is commissioned to write a review of the decade since the last issue of the magazine devoted to women artists.<ref name ='Barton 1993'/> A number of exhibitions exploring women in New Zealand's art history and feminist art issues are staged around the country, including ''[[Alter / Image]]'' in Wellington and Auckland, ''Mediatrix : new works by seven women artists'' at [[Artspace NZ|Artspace]] in Auckland (curated by Priscilla Pitts and featuring [[Mary-Louise Browne]], Denise Kum, [[Julia Morison]], Marie Shannon, Deborah Smith, Aromea Tahiwi and [[Barbara Tuck]]); ''Unruly Practices'' (a series of solo projects by feminist artists living in Auckland - [[Carole Shepheard]], [[Claudia Pond Eyley]], Mary McIntyre, [[Christine Hellyar]] and [[Sylvia Siddell]]) at [[Auckland Art Gallery]], ''White Camellias : a century of women's artmaking in Canterbury'' and ''Women on women : art in Dunedin since 1893'' at the [[Dunedin Public Art Gallery]], curated by Linda Tyler.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mediatrix : new work by seven women artists : an exhibition to mark the centenary of women's suffrage in New Zealand|url=http://natlib.govt.nz/records/22161487|website=National Library of New Zealand|accessdate=25 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=White Camellias: A Century of Art Making by Canterbury Women|url=http://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/exhibitions/white-camellias|website=Christchurch Art Gallery|accessdate=25 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Women on women : art in Dunedin since 1893|url=http://natlib.govt.nz/records/22206191|website=National Library of New Zealand|accessdate=25 December 2015}}</ref> ''Alter / Image'' was also one of four inaugural exhibitions, all featuring female artists, that marked the opening of [[City Gallery Wellington]] in its new location in the old Public Library building in Wellington's Civic Square; the others were ''[[Rosemarie Trockel]]'', ''Te Whare Puanga'' (recent weaving and tivaevae by Maori and Pacific Island women in Wellington) and ''He Tohu: The New Zealand Room'', a site-specific project by [[Jacqueline Fraser]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Exhibition advertisement|journal=Art New Zealand|date=Spring 1993|issue=68|page=unpaginated}}</ref> An updated version of Anne Kirker's 1986 book ''New Zealand Women Artists'' is published as ''New Zealand women artists : a survey of 150 years'' by Reed Methuen.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kirker|first1=Anne|title=New Zealand women artists : a survey of 150 years|date=1993|publisher=Auckland|location=Reed Methuen|isbn=9768097302}}</ref>\n\n'''1994'''\n\nAustralian art magazine ''Artlink'' devotes its Autumn issue to 'Art & the Feminist Project'. The issue features articles by New Zealand writers  [[Tina Barton]] ('Making (a) difference: Suffrage year celebrations and the visual arts in New Zealand') and Anne Kirker ('Re-orienting feminism in Aotearoa').<ref>{{cite web|title=Art & the Feminist Project|url=https://www.artlink.com.au/issues/1410/art-26-the-feminist-project/|website=Artlink|accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==2000s==\n\n'''2000'''\n\nThe [[Govett-Brewster Art Gallery]] stages ''In glorious dreams'', an exhibition of new work by women artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=In glorious dreams|url=http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/vwebv/holdingsInfo?bibId=610512|website=National Library of New Zealand catalogue|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2001'''\n\nArtist [[Jacqueline Fraser]] is selected, along with Peter Robinson, to represent New Zealand in its first participation at the [[Venice Biennale]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mane-Wheoki|first1=Jonathan|title=Contemporary M\u0101ori art \u2013 ng\u0101 toi h\u014du - Contemporary M\u0101ori art in the 2000s|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/contemporary-maori-art-nga-toi-hou/page-5|website=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''2002'''\n\nThe Govett-Brewster Art Gallery stages ''Go Girl'', a survey of the work of photographer Fiona Clark. The exhibition includes works withdrawn from the 1975 exhibition ''The Active Eye'' after accusations of indecency relating to their depiction of the LGBT community.<ref>{{cite web|title=Go Girl at New Plymouth\u2019s Govett-Brewster Gallery|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU0209/S00079/go-girl-at-new-plymouths-govett-brewster-gallery.htm|website=Scoop.co.nz|accessdate=23 February 2016|date=25 September 2002}}</ref>\n\n'''2004'''\n\nThe Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa stages ''Judy Darragh: So ... You Made It'', the only solo exhibition of a contemporary New Zealand artist presented at the museum between its opening in 1998 and the 'Toi Art' refreshment that opened in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Judy Darragh: So ... you made it?|url=http://www.tepapa.govt.nz/WhatsOn/exhibitions/Pages/JudyDarragh.aspx|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tonagrewa|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2008'''\n\nThe Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa presents the exhibition ''We are unsuitable for framing''. Curated by Charlotte Huddleston, the exhibition is titled after a work by Barbara Kruger held in the museum's collection and included in the artist's 1988 exhibition in Wellington. It includes works produced between 1974 and 2005 and aimed to explore 'aspects of identity, gender, sexuality, and mythology'.<ref>{{cite web|title=We are unsuitable for framing|url=http://www.tepapa.govt.nz/WhatsOn/exhibitions/Pages/WeAreUnsuitableForFraming.aspx|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2009'''\n\nThe [[Adam Art Gallery]] holds a workshop titled 'Out Loud: Using the \u2018F\u2019 Word Today', featuring a range of female curators and artists, to accompany its survey exhibition of the work of [[Vivian Lynn]], '' I, HERE, NOW Vivian Lynn''.<ref>{{cite web|title=February-March 2009|url=http://www.adamartgallery.org.nz/calendar/february-march/|website=Adam Art Gallery|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==2010 - present==\n\n'''2012'''\n\n[[The Dowse Art Museum]] stages the touring  exhibition ''In Spite of Ourselves: Approaching Documentary'', which includes a work by Qatari/US artist, Sophia Al-Maria, ''For Your Eyes Only'' (2007) which shows female members of a family preparing for a wedding in a space in a house only used by women and children. The artists requests that the video work only be shown to female visitors: when the museum complies with this request protests are made that men are being excluded from the museum.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Spite of Ourselves: Approaching Documentary|url=http://dowse.org.nz/exhibitions/detail/in-spite-of-ourselves-approaching-documentary|website=The Dowse Art Museum|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=In Spite of Everything|url=http://dowse.org.nz/news/blog/2012/in-spite-of-everything|website=The Dowse Art Museum|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2013'''\n\nWriter Thomasin Sleigh publishes an analysis of the contemporary editorial approach of ''Art New Zealand'', concluding that 'the artist most likely for Art New Zealand to run an article on would be a Pakeha painter, and his work would most likely be written about by a Pakeha man employed by an academic institution.'<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sleigh|first1=Thomasin|title=The Stuttering Conversation:  Art New Zealand in 2013|url=http://lumiere.net.nz/index.php/art-new-zealand-in-2013/|website=The Lumiere Reader|accessdate=22 February 2016|date=21 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''2014'''\n\nArt History honours students at the University of Auckland organise ''Voicing the Visible'', an exhibition of female and feminist artists work from the university's collection for the Gus Fisher Gallery.<ref>{{cite web|title=Voicing the Visible|url=http://www.ingenio-magazine.com/voicing-the-visible/|website=Ingenio|publisher=University of Auckland Alumni organisation|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2015'''\n\n[[Enjoy Public Art Gallery]] in Wellington presents ''Enjoy Feminisms'', an exhibition programme that sought to demonstrate the multiple meanings of feminism to contemporary artists, and publishes ''Love Feminisms'', an online journal to accompany the exhibition programme.<ref>{{cite web|title=Enjoy Feminisms|url=http://www.enjoy.org.nz/node/3665|website=Enjoy Public Art Gallery|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Love Feminisms|url=http://journal.enjoy.org.nz/love-feminisms/editorial|website=Enjoy Public Art Gallery|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Adam Art Gallery]] presents ''Fragments of a World: Artists Working in Film and Photography 1973\u20131987'', curated by Dr Sandy Callister, an exhibition investigating 'the intersection of feminism, new technologies, and a disruptive epoch'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fragments of a World|url=http://www.adamartgallery.org.nz/past-exhibitions/10053/|website=Adam Art Gallery|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[The Dowse Art Museum]] in Lower Hutt organises an 'Art + Feminism' Wikipedia edit-a-thon to improve coverage of New Zealand women artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Art + Feminism edit-a-thon|url=http://dowse.org.nz/events/art-feminism-wikipedia-edit-a-thon|website=The Dowse Art Museum|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2016'''\n\nThe Dowse Art Museum organises 'Four Waves of Feminism', a symposium exploring current and historical feminist art, activity and research.<ref>{{cite web|title=Four Waves of Feminism|url=http://dowse.org.nz/events/four-waves-of-feminism|website=The Dowse Art Museum|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nBarbara Brookes' ''A History of New Zealand Women'' is published by [[Bridget Williams Books]]. Heavily illustrated with the work of women artists including [[Olivia Spencer Bower]], [[Rita Angus]], [[Margaret Stoddart]] and [[Louise Henderson]], the reproductions are presented 'not simply as illustrations for the immediate text but as a narrative in themselves. ... this is, presenting a woman's perspective.'<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brookes|first1=Barbara|title=A history of New Zealand women|date=2016|publisher=Bridget Williams Books|location=Wellington|isbn=9780908321476|page=486}}</ref>\n\nThe Adam Art Gallery presents ''Bad Visual Systems'', an exhibition by Berlin-based, New Zealand-born artist Ruth Buchanan. For the exhibition Buchanan shows the work of German artists Judith Hopf and [[Marianne Wex]]. The exhibition presents panels from Wex's photographic book ''Let\u2019s Take Back Our Space''; sheets from the book had been printed in a 1984 edition of the feminist magazine ''Broadsheet'' when Wex was living in Wellington.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bad Visual Systems|url=http://www.adamartgallery.org.nz/current-exhibition/|website=Adam Art Gallery|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''2018'''\n\n2018 marks the 125th anniversary of women's suffrage in New Zealand.\n\nChristchurch Art Gallery presents ''We Do This'', an exhibition of work by women artists. largely from the gallery's permanent collection, in a 'recharged contemporary hang to mark 125 years of women\u2019s suffrage.'<ref>{{cite web |title=We Do This |url=https://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/exhibitions/we-do-this |website=Christchurch Art Gallery Te Puna o Waiwhet\u016b |accessdate=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Dowse Art Museum presents \"Embodied Knowledge\", an exhibition of \"significant sculptural works made by women artists during a tumultuous period of Aotearoa New Zealand\u2019s art history\" featuring older and new works by Christine Hellyar, Maureen Lander, Vivian Lynn, Pauline Rhodes, The Estate of L. Budd.<ref>{{cite web |title=Embodied Knowledge |url=http://dowse.org.nz/exhibitions/detail/embodied-knowledge |website=dowse.org.nz |accessdate=25 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> A pendant exhibition, ''Can Tame Anything'', features work by a newer generation of women artists and collectives; Ruth Buchanan, Alicia Frankovich, Mata Aho Collective, Sriwhana Spong.<ref>{{cite web |title=Can Tame Anything |url=http://dowse.org.nz/exhibitions/detail/can-tame-anything |website=dowse.org.nz |accessdate=25 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''2019'''\n\nThe Auckland Art Gallery presents ''Guerrilla Girls: Reinventing the \u2018F\u2019 Word \u2013 Feminism!'', an exhibition of work by the famous feminist art collective [[Guerilla Girls]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Guerrilla Girls: Reinventing the \u2018F\u2019 Word \u2013 Feminism! |url=https://www.aucklandartgallery.com/whats-on/exhibition/guerrilla-girls-reinventing-the-f-word-feminism |website=Auckland Art Gallery |accessdate=25 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The exhibition includes statistical analysis presented in the collective's signature format of the proportion of exhibitions of women artists at the gallery.\n\n[[The Spinoff]] publishes Anna Knox's investigative article 'Gender bias and art in Aotearoa: a Spinoff survey reveals the harsh reality'.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Knox |first1=Anna |title=Gender bias and art in Aotearoa: a Spinoff survey reveals the harsh reality |url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/art/30-09-2019/gender-bias-and-art-in-aotearoa-a-spinoff-survey-reveals-the-harsh-reality/ |website=The Spinoff |accessdate=25 October 2019 |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Feminism in New Zealand]]\n*[[List of New Zealand artists]]\n*[[Australian feminist art timeline]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Feminism}}\n{{Westernart}}\n\n<!-- STOP! Be warned that by using this process instead of Articles for Creation, this article is subject to scrutiny. As an article in \"mainspace\", it will be DELETED if there are problems, not just declined. If you wish to use AfC, please return to the Wizard and continue from there. -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feminist Art Movement}}\n[[Category:Art movements]]\n[[Category:Contemporary art]]\n[[Category:Feminist theory]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Political art]]\n[[Category:New Zealand art]]\n[[Category:Feminism in New Zealand]]\n", "name_user": "RoseInCharge", "label": "safe", "comment": "Link added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_the_feminist_art_movement_in_New_Zealand"}
{"title_page": "Cuz I Love You", "text_new": "{{about||the single by Slade|Coz I Luv You|the title track|Cuz I Love You (song)}}\n{{short description|2019 studio album by Lizzo}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Cuz I Love You\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Lizzo]]\n| cover      = Lizzo - Cuz I Love You.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2019|04|19|mf=y}}\n| recorded   = \n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"NME\"/><ref name=\"The Guardian\"/><ref name=\"DIY\">{{cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2019/04/17/lizzo-cuz-i-love-you-album-review|title=Lizzo \u2013 Cuz I Love You|website=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]|last=Finn|first=Rachel|date=April 17, 2019|accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"The Line of Best Fit\"/>|[[funk]]<ref name=\"DIY\"/><ref name=\"The Line of Best Fit\"/>|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"DIY\"/><ref name=\"Clash\"/>|[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]<ref name=\"Clash\">{{cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/reviews/lizzo-cuz-i-love-you|title=Lizzo \u2013 Cuz I Love You|work=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|last=Akinfenwa|first=Jumi|date=April 17, 2019|accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref>|[[Rock music|rock]]<ref name=\"The Line of Best Fit\"/>|[[Soul music|soul]]<ref>{{cite web |title=The 100 Best Albums of the 2010s |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/best-albums-2010s-ranked-913997/lizzo-cuz-i-love-you-album-917489/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 33:18\n| label      = {{hlist|Nice Life|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Lizzo]]|[[Ricky Reed]]|Nate Mercureau|[[X Ambassadors]]|[[Oak Felder|OAK]]|Sweater Beats|Dan Farber|Tobias Wincorn|Mike Sabath|Zaire Koalo|Trevorious}}\n| prev_title = [[Coconut Oil (EP)|Coconut Oil]]\n| prev_year  = 2016\n| misc       = {{Singles\n| name        = Cuz I Love You\n| type        = studio\n| single1     = [[Juice (Lizzo song)|Juice]]\n| single1date = January 4, 2019\n| single2     = [[Tempo (Lizzo song)|Tempo]]\n| single2date = July 26, 2019\n| single3     = [[Cuz I Love You (song)|Cuz I Love You]]\n| single3date = January 28, 2020<ref name=\"Top 40/M Future Releases\">{{cite web |title=Top 40/M Future Releases |url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases |publisher=All Access Media Group |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''''Cuz I Love You''''' is the third studio album and debut major label LP by American rapper and singer [[Lizzo]]. It was released through Nice Life and [[Atlantic Records]] on April 19, 2019.<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/lizzo-announces-new-album-and-tour/|title=Lizzo Announces New Album and Tour|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Monroe|first=Jazz|date=January 28, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> The album features guest appearances from American rappers [[Missy Elliott]] and [[Gucci Mane]]. It spawned the singles \"[[Juice (Lizzo song)|Juice]]\" and \"[[Tempo (Lizzo song)|Tempo]]\", the latter of which is a collaboration with Missy Elliott. The deluxe edition of the album was released on May 3 and includes the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number one single \"[[Truth Hurts (song)|Truth Hurts]]\". The deluxe edition was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] at the [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards]], and won [[Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporary Album|Best Urban Contemporary Album]].\n\n==Background==\nThe album is Lizzo's first release since her 2016 ''[[Coconut Oil (EP)|Coconut Oil]]'' EP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/01/28/lizzo-cuz-i-love-you-release-date-tour|title=Lizzo confirms CUZ I LOVE YOU album details|work=[[The Fader]]|last=Renshaw|first=David|date=January 28, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> Lizzo stated at the album preview party at the Crazy Girls strip club in Hollywood on January 30 that she has been working on the album for three years. She also previewed a collaboration with [[Missy Elliott]] titled \"Tempo\" that will appear on the album.<ref name=\"Pride\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pride.com/music/2019/1/31/secure-your-wigs-lizzo-has-collab-missy-elliott-it-slaps|title=Secure Your Wigs: Lizzo Has a Collab with Missy Elliott (& It Slaps!)|website=[[Pride.com]]|last=Henderson|first=Taylor|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> Along with the lead single \"Juice\", the album includes the \"empowering dance track\" \"Like a Girl\" and a song dedicated to an ex titled \"Jerome\".<ref name=\"Pride\"/>\n\n==Promotion==\nLizzo announced the album in late January 2019, and on February 13, shared the album's cover art, on which she appears [[nude]]. ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'' called the cover a \"stunning glow-up, and a transformation for Lizzo\", going on to say that \"Fat, and especially fat and Black bodies are rarely treated with such care by photographers, let alone on album covers that will sit on [[Target Corporation|Target]] and [[Walmart]] shelves.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.papermag.com/lizzo-nude-album-cover-2628795044.html|title=Lizzo Drops Nude 'Cuz I Love You' Album Cover|work=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|last=Goldfine|first=Jael|date=February 13, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe album was supported by two world [[concert tour|tours]]: Cuz I Love You Tour (2019) and [[Cuz I Love You Too Tour]] (2019-2020).\n\n==Singles==\n\"Juice\" was released as the lead single from the record on January 4, 2019.<ref name=\"RS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/song-you-need-to-know-lizzo-juice-777189/|title=Song You Need to Know: Lizzo, 'Juice'|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Hoard|first=Christian|date=January 11, 2019|accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> The single became Lizzo's first commercial hit, entering component R&B charts in the United States, while also reaching the top twenty in Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/lizzo/chart-history/hot-adult-r-and-b-airplay|title=Lizzo Chart History|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/lizzo/chart-history/r-and-b-songs|title=Lizzo Chart History|website=Billboard|access-date=January 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20190301/41/|title=Official Scottish Singles Sales Chart Top 100|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=March 22, 2019}}</ref> The single was promoted with Lizzo's debut television performance on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'', and a later performance on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/hiphop/lizzo-juice-performance-ellen/|title=Lizzo's Single 'Juice' Makes Its Television Debut With A Terrific Live Performance|website=[[Uproxx]]|last=Gilke|first=Chloe|date=January 29, 2019|accessdate=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/lizzo-performs-juice-with-dancers-disco-ball-on-fallon-watch/|title=Lizzo Performs 'Juice' With Dancers, Disco Ball on 'Fallon': Watch|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Blais-Billie|first=Braudie|date=February 6, 2019|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"Tempo\", featuring American rap artist [[Missy Elliott]] was released as a single on July 26, 2019.  The song also was given a music video that premiered on YouTube the same date.<ref>{{Citation|last=Lizzo Music|title=Lizzo - Tempo (feat. Missy Elliott) [Official Music Video]|date=2019-07-26|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Srq1FqFPwj0|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\n\"Cuz I Love You\", originally released as a promotional single on February 14, 2019, was released as a single to Top 40 radio on January 28, 2020.<ref name=\"Top 40/M Future Releases\">{{cite web |title=Top 40/M Future Releases |url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases |publisher=All Access Media Group |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Promotional singles===\nThe album's title track was released as the first promotional single on February 14, 2019, alongside the song's music video.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/02/14/lizzo-cuz-i-love-you-music-video-album-release-date|title=Lizzo bares her heart in the 'Cuz I Love You' music video|website=[[The Fader]]|last=Darville|first=Jordan|date=February 14, 2019|accessdate=March 22, 2019}}</ref> \"Tempo\" featuring [[Missy Elliott]] was released as the album's second promotional single on March 20, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/03/lizzo-tempo-missy-elliott-listen/|title=Missy Elliott Joins Lizzo on New Song 'Tempo'|website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=March 21, 2019|last=Daramola|first=Israel}}</ref> \"Tempo\" went on to chart at number 21 on the US [[Digital Song Sales]] chart, Lizzo's first entry on a [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] component chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/lizzo/chart-history/digital-song-sales|title=Lizzo Digital Song Sales Billboard Chart History|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 7.9/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/9849/Lizzo-Cuz-I-Love-You.aspx|title=Cuz I Love You by Lizzo reviews|website=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n| MC = 84/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/cuz-i-love-you/lizzo|title=Cuz I Love You by Lizzo Reviews and Tracks|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/cuz-i-love-you-mw0003252453|title=Cuz I Love You \u2013 Lizzo|website=[[AllMusic]]|last=Phares|first=Heather|accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2score = B<ref name=\"The A.V. Club\">{{cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/lizzo-loves-herself-and-learns-to-love-somebody-else-1834151268|title=Lizzo loves herself, and learns to love somebody else, on the empowered yet tender Cuz I Love You|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Rife|first=Katie|date=April 19, 2019|accessdate=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Daily Telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/lizzo-cuz-love-review-has-hiding-voice/|title=Lizzo, Cuz I Love You, review: where has she been hiding that voice?|website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|last=McCormick|first=Neil|authorlink=Neil McCormick|date=April 17, 2019|accessdate=June 15, 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/apr/18/lizzo-cuz-i-love-you-review-body-positive-pop|title=Lizzo: Cuz I Love You review \u2013 body-positive pop with its foot on the gas|website=[[The Guardian]]|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|authorlink=Alexis Petridis|date=April 18, 2019|accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-review-lizzo-cuz-i-love-you-fat-white-family-serfs-up-cage-elephant-social-cues-a8875081.html|title=Album reviews: Lizzo \u2013 Cuz I Love You, Fat White Family \u2013 Serfs Up! and Cage the Elephant \u2013 Social Cues|website=[[The Independent]]|last1=Beaumont|first1=Mark|authorlink1=Mark Beaumont (journalist)|last2=O'Connor|first2=Roisin|last3=Pollard|first3=Alexandra|date=April 18, 2019|accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/lizzo-cuz-i-love-you-album-review-2478435|title=Lizzo \u2013 'Cuz I Love You' review|website=[[NME]]|last=Kasambala|first=Natty|date=April 19, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[The Observer]]''\n| rev7score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"The Observer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/apr/20/lizzo-cuz-i-love-you-review|title=Lizzo: Cuz I Love You review \u2013 on the bright side of history|website=[[The Observer]]|last=Empire|first=Kitty|authorlink=Kitty Empire|date=April 20, 2019|accessdate=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev8score = 6.5/10<ref name=\"PitchforkReview\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/lizzo-cuz-i-love-you/|title=Lizzo: Cuz I Love You|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Kameir|first=Ramiya|date=April 22, 2019|accessdate=April 23, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/review-lizzo-cuz-i-love-you-824705/|title=Lizzo Is Her Own Hero on the Legend-Making \u2018Cuz I Love You\u2019|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Sheffield|date=April 22, 2019|accessdate=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' ([[Robert Christgau#Consumer Guide|Expert Witness]])\n| rev10score = A\u2212<ref name=\"Vice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/neakdb/robert-christgau-on-lizzos-casual-confidence|title=Robert Christgau on Lizzo's Casual Confidence|website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=June 15, 2019|accessdate=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n''Cuz I Love You'' received widespread acclaim from [[Music journalism|music critics]] upon its initial release. At Metacritic, which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album has an average score of 84, based on 24 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n\nReviewing the album for [[AllMusic]], Heather Phares praised ''Cuz I Love You'' as \"a triumphant showcase for every part of Lizzo's talent, physicality and sexuality.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Jumi Akinfenwa of ''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]'' stated that by \"Offering up a mix of pop, hip-hop, R&B and a sprinkling of trap and neo soul for good measure, Lizzo covers all bases and serves the perfect introduction to her world for mainstream audiences.\"<ref name=\"Clash\"/> ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]'' magazine's Rachel Finn gave a positive evaluation of the album, writing that \"Lizzo's vibrant personality and humour shining through a set of tracks that switches through elements of funk, pop and R&B with ease.\"<ref name=\"DIY\"/>\n\nIn an article for ''[[NME]]'', reviewer Natty Kasambala described the album as being \"as flawlessly genre-spanning as Lizzo herself: pop at its core, but with constant references to her jazz roots and historical love of twerking.\"<ref name=\"NME\"/> Claire Biddles at ''[[The Line of Best Fit]]'' shared similar sentiments, calling the album \"Charming, addictive and seemingly effortless, ''Cuz I Love You'' is Lizzo's declaration of superstardom.\"<ref name=\"The Line of Best Fit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/reviews/albums/lizzo-cuz-i-love-you-album-review|title=Cuz I Love You is Lizzo's declaration of superstardom|website=[[The Line of Best Fit]]|last=Biddles|first=Claire|date=April 15, 2019|accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]''{{'}}s Zachary Hoskins concluded that \"Lizzo's talent has always been evident, but this album\u2019s material, her strongest to date, allows her put it on full display. By the languorous, seductive neo-soul of closing track \"Lingerie,\" her enthusiasm is as contagious as it is well-earned.\"<ref name=\"Slant\">{{cite web|title=Review: Lizzo's Cuz I Love You Is a Vessel of Pure Exuberence|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review-lizzos-cuz-i-love-you-is-a-vessel-for-pure-exuberance/|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|last=Hoskins|first=Zachary|date=April 22, 2019|accessdate=April 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome reviewers were more reserved in their assessments of the album. In a review for ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Alexis Petridis]] felt that \"Lizzo has something to say, and a smart way of saying it ... but the potency of what\u2019s here would seem more potent still if it had been allowed a little room to breathe ... Instead, ''Cuz I Love You'' keeps its foot pressed down hard on the accelerator for half an hour in an attempt to ram-raid the charts.\"<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/> Rawiya Kameir was also critical in the review for ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'', claiming that \"Despite her obvious skill and charisma, some of the album\u2019s 11 songs are burdened with overwrought production, awkward turns of phrase, and ham-handed rapping.\"<ref name=\"PitchforkReview\"/>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! scope=\"col\" | Year{{efn|Indicates the year of ceremony. Each year is linked to the article about the awards held that year, wherever possible.}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[BET Hip Hop Awards]]\n| [[2019 BET Hip Hop Awards|2019]]\n| [[BET Hip Hop Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8529768/2019-bet-hip-hop-awards-nominations-list |title=Cardi B Leads 2019 BET Hip Hop Awards With 10 Nominations: Exclusive|last=Lamarre|first=Carl|date=September 12, 2019|work=Billboard|access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Grammy Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards|2020]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/2020-grammy-awards-complete-nominees-list |title=2020 GRAMMY Awards: Complet